{{Infobox rocket stage |name = Exploration Upper Stage |image = |caption = |manufacturer = [[Boeing]]<ref name=sne>{{cite web|title=NASA, Boeing Finalize $2.8B SLS Core Stage Contract|url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/civil-space/41139nasa-boeing-finalize-28b-sls-core-stage-contract|website=SpaceNews.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014}}</ref> |country = US |rockets = [[Space Launch System|SLS]] Block 1B <ref name=nsfe>{{cite web|title=NASA confirms EUS for SLS Block IB design and EM-2 flight|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2014/06/nasa-confirms-eus-sls-block-ib-design-em-2-flight/|website=NASASpaceflight.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014}}</ref> |height = not to exceed {{convert|60|ft|abbr=on|order=flip}} |diameter = {{convert|8.4|m|abbr=on}} |propmass = up to {{convert|285,000|lb|abbr=on|order=flip}} |engines = 4 [[RL10|RL10C-3]]<ref name=rl10>{{cite web|last=Bergin|first=Chris|title=MSFC propose Aerojet Rocketdyne supply EUS engines|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2016/04/msfc-aerojet-rocketdyne-eus-engines/ |publisher=NASASpaceFlight|accessdate=April 8, 2016|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=RL10C-Oct>[https://www.nasa.gov/exploration/systems/sls/proven-engine-packs-big-in-space-punch-for-nasa-s-sls-rocket.html Proven Engine Packs Big, In-Space Punch for NASA’s SLS Rocket. Oct 2016]</ref> |thrust = {{convert|99,000|lbf|kN|abbr=on|order=flip|lk=out}} |time = |fuel = [[Liquid oxygen|LOX]]/[[Liquid hydrogen|LH<sub>2</sub>]] }}
The '''Exploration Upper Stage (EUS)''' is being developed as a large second stage for Block 1B of the [[Space Launch System]] (SLS), succeeding Block 1's [[Delta Cryogenic Second Stage|Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage]]. It will be powered by four [[RL10]]C-3<ref name=RL10C-Oct/> engines burning [[Liquid oxygen|LOX]]/[[Liquid hydrogen|LH<sub>2</sub>]] to produce a total of {{convert|99,000|lbf|kN|abbr=on|order=flip|lk=out}} thrust. {{asof|February 2015}} the SLS Block 1B is baselined at 105 metric tons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Advanced Boosters progress towards a solid future for SLS|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2015/02/advanced-boosters-towards-solid-future-sls/|accessdate=2015-03-12|publisher=NasaSpaceflight.com|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref> The EUS is expected to first fly on the [[Exploration Mission 3]] launch of the SLS scheduled for 2023.<ref>{{cite news|title=NASA updates Lunar Gateway plans|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2018/09/nasa-lunar-gateway-plans/|accessdate=2018-10-05|publisher=NasaSpaceflight.com|date=2018-09-11}}</ref>
==Development== The Block 1 configuration of SLS will have the ability to insert 70 metric tons<ref name=":0">{{cite web|title=SLS|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/sls.htm|website=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=July 25, 2014}}</ref> into low Earth orbit (LEO) using [[Space Shuttle|Shuttle-derived]] 5-segment [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster|Solid Rocket Boosters]] and a core stage powered by four [[Space Shuttle Main Engine|RS-25]] engines. Its second stage, the [[Delta Cryogenic Second Stage#ICPS|ICPS]], will be considered part of the 70 t payload and on [[Exploration Mission 1|EM-1]] it will be placed, along with the Orion crew capsule, on a 1,800&nbsp;km by -93&nbsp;km [[suborbital]] trajectory to ensure safe disposal of the core stage. At apogee, the ICPS will perform an insertion burn to raise the perigee and put itself and Orion into a stable orbit, and will later perform a [[translunar injection]] burn to send the uncrewed Orion capsule on a [[circumlunar]] excursion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Space Launch System Data Sheet|url=http://www.spacelaunchreport.com/sls0.html|website=SpaceLaunchReport.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014}}</ref>
To improve on the 70 metric ton Block 1, NASA considered a Block 1A upgrade which would replace the Shuttle-heritage boosters with advanced solid or [[liquid rocket boosters|liquid boosters]], and a Block 1B upgrade which would develop an improved second stage. This improved stage was originally named the Dual Use Upper Stage (DUUS, pronounced "duce")<ref name=nsfpdr>{{cite web|title=SLS prepares for PDR – Evolution eyes Dual-Use Upper Stage|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2013/06/sls-pdr-evolved-rocket-dual-upper-stage/|website=NASASpaceflight.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014}}</ref> but was later renamed the Exploration Upper Stage (EUS) due to DUUS sounding like a profanity in Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bergin|first1=Chris|title=SLS positioning for ARRM and Europa missions|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2014/03/sls-positioning-arrm-europa-missions/|website=NASA Spaceflight|accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref> [[Image:S-IV rocket stage.jpg|right|thumb|200px|A diagram of the 6 engined [[S-IV]], the 2nd stage of the [[Saturn I]]. In comparison to this cluster of [[RL10|RL10A-3]] engines, the SLS Block IB 2nd stage, the EUS, will likewise contain a cluster of these engines but will surpass the clustered performance of the above S-IV with just 4 [[RL10|RL10B-2]] derived engines and do so without the weight saving [[S-IV|common bulkhead]] of the S-IV.]] Following concerns that the more powerful Block 1A boosters would have resulted in high acceleration during launch, which would have been unsuitable for the Orion crew vehicle and could have resulted in a costly redesign of the SLS core,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bergin|first1=Chris|title=Wind Tunnel testing conducted on SLS configurations, including Block 1B|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/07/wind-tunnel-testing-sls-configurations-block-1b/|website=NASA SpaceFlight|accessdate=2015-03-12}}</ref> NASA announced in 2014 that it would proceed with development of Block 1B with the EUS before advanced boosters.<ref name=nsfe/> In April 2016 it was reported NASA has chosen to use a design based on four [[RL10]]-C3 engines for the EUS,<ref name=rl10 /> and in Oct 2016 NASA confirmed they had ordered 10 of the engines.<ref name="RL10C-Oct" />
==Role & comparable stages== The EUS is to complete the SLS's [[boost phase|ascent phase]] and then re-ignite to send its payload to destinations beyond [[low Earth orbit]], similar in function to the 3rd stage on the [[Saturn V]], the [[Rocketdyne J-2|J-2]] powered [[S-IVB]] but closer to the 2nd stage on the [[Saturn I]], the [[S-IV]] in engine layout, as it contained a cluster of RL-10 engines and was likewise a 2nd stage on the vehicle stack.
The 2nd stage of the SLS Block 1B, the EUS, powered by a cluster of four RL10 engines will produce slightly more thrust than the Saturn I's six engined [[S-IV]] of the 1960s.
Prior to finalization of second stage options for the SLS Block 1B, a more powerful [[Earth Departure Stage]] was under development, which would have been powered by up to three of the much more powerful [[J-2X]] engines.<ref>{{cite web|title=SLS Launch Vehicle specifications take shape as development continues|url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/03/sls-specifications-take-shape-development-continues/|website=NASASpaceflight.com|accessdate=July 24, 2014}}</ref> Technological development of the J-2X was expected to take considerably more time, so the EDS was dropped in favor of the EUS, which will use the already-developed RL10. According to NASA, the J-2X will be overpowered for the lunar and asteroid missions of the Block 1 and 1B SLS; its development has been put on hold (though not abandoned) until stages capable of transferring heavy payloads to Mars are required (currently expected in the 2030s).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/awin/nasa-s-j-2x-engine-be-mothballed-after-testing|title=NASA’s J-2X Engine To Be Mothballed After Testing|website=aviationweek.com|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref>
