'''Mucosal immunology''' is the study of [[immune system]] responses that occur at [[Mucous membrane|mucosal membranes]] of the [[Gastrointestinal tract|intestines]], the [[Genitourinary system|urogenital tract]] and the [[respiratory system]], i.e., surfaces that are in contact with the external environment.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nature.com/subjects/mucosal-immunology|title=Mucosal immunology - Latest research and news {{!}} Nature|website=www.nature.com|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> In [[Health|healthy states]], the mucosal immune system provides protection against [[pathogen]]s but maintains a tolerance towards non-harmful [[Commensalism|commensal]] microbes and benign environmental substances.<ref name=":0" /> For example, in the oral and gut mucosa, the secretion of IgA provides an immune response to potential antigens in food without a large and unnecessary systemic immune response.<ref>Helbert, M. (2017). Immunology for medical students (Third ed.). Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier.</ref> Since the mucosal membranes are the primary contact point between a host and its environment, a large amount of [[Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue|secondary lymphoid tissue]] is found here. The [[mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue]], or MALT, provides the organism with an important first line of defense. Along with the [[spleen]] and [[lymph nodes]], the [[tonsils]] and MALT are also considered to be secondary lymphoid tissue.<ref>Ibid., 84.</ref> The mucosal immune system provides three main functions: serving as the body's first line defense from antigens and infection, preventing systemic immune responses to commensal bacteria and food antigens (primarily food proteins in the [[Gut-associated lymphoid tissue]], so-called [[oral tolerance]]), and regulating appropriate immune responses to pathogens encountered on a daily basis.<ref>Ibid., 86.</ref>

At birth, the [[infant|neonate]]'s mucosal immune system is relatively undeveloped, but the colonization of [[intestinal flora]] promotes its development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Torow|first=N.|last2=Marsland|first2=B. J.|last3=Hornef|first3=M. W.|last4=Gollwitzer|first4=E. S.|date=2016-09-21|title=Neonatal mucosal immunology|journal=Mucosal Immunology|doi=10.1038/mi.2016.81|issn=1935-3456|pmid=27649929}}</ref>

Because of its front-line status within the immune system, the mucosal immune system is being investigated for use in vaccines for various afflictions,<ref>[http://www.scq.ubc.ca/mucosal-immunity-and-vaccines/ Mucosal Immunity and Vaccines], August 2003</ref> including [[AIDS]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pavot|first1=V|last2=Rochereau|first2=N|last3=Lawrence|first3=P|last4=Girard|first4=MP|last5=Genin|first5=C|last6=Verrier|first6=B|last7=Paul|first7=S|title=Recent progress in HIV vaccines inducing mucosal immune responses.|journal=AIDS|date=31 July 2014|volume=28|issue=12|pages=1701–18|pmid=25009956|doi=10.1097/qad.0000000000000308}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bourinbaiar |first1=Aldar S. |last2=Metadilogkul |first2=Orapun |last3=Jirathitikal |first3=Vichai |title=Mucosal AIDS Vaccines |journal=Viral Immunology |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=427–45 |year=2003 |pmid=14733732 |doi=10.1089/088282403771926274}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simerska |first1=Pavla |last2=Moyle |first2=Peter M. |last3=Olive |first3=Colleen |last4=Toth |first4=Istvan |title=Oral Vaccine Delivery - New Strategies and Technologies |journal=Current Drug Delivery |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=347–58 |year=2009 |pmid=19534712 |doi=10.2174/156720109789000537}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Silin |first1=Dmytro S. |last2=Lyubomska |first2=Oksana V. |last3=Jirathitikal |first3=Vichai |last4=Bourinbaiar |first4=Aldar S. |title=Oral vaccination: where we are? |journal=Expert Opinion on Drug Delivery |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=323–40 |year=2007 |pmid=17683247 |doi=10.1517/17425247.4.4.323}}</ref> and [[allergies]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wild |first1=C. |last2=Wallner |first2=M. |last3=Hufnagl |first3=K. |last4=Fuchs |first4=H. |last5=Hoffmann-Sommergruber |first5=K. |last6=Breiteneder |first6=H. |last7=Scheiner |first7=O. |last8=Ferreira |first8=F. |last9=Wiedermann |first9=U. |title=A recombinant allergen chimer as novel mucosal vaccine candidate for prevention of multi-sensitivities |journal=Allergy |volume=62 |issue=1 |pages=33–41 |year=2007 |pmid=17156339 |doi=10.1111/j.1398-9995.2006.01245.x }}</ref>

